<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/21334742-patrick-schl-ter"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1371307331i/21334742._UX100_CR0,9,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/21334742-patrick-schl-ter">Patrick Schl√ºter</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I had read PoH before Angel&apos;s game and enjoyed it immensely. I re-read it after Angel&apos;s game and enjoyed it even more. The back-story of Angel&apos;s game <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">‚Ä¶more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I had read PoH before Angel's game and enjoyed it immensely. I re-read it after Angel's game and enjoyed it even more. The back-story of Angel's game filled the secondary characters with so much life that the story changed significantly. So I tend to think that the books should be read in the right order to be enjoyed to their fullest.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
