<div id="review_468780641" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/468780641" />
    <a title="Magdalena aka A Bookaholic Swede" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1379514-magdalena-aka-a-bookaholic-swede"><img alt="Magdalena aka A Bookaholic Swede" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1487436758p2/1379514.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/468780641?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Magdalena aka A Bookaholic Swede" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Magdalena aka A Bookaholic Swede" href="/user/show/1379514-magdalena-aka-a-bookaholic-swede">Magdalena aka A Bookaholic Swede</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9789100129934" href="/book/show/16080627-himlens-f-nge">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1379514-magdalena-aka-a-bookaholic-swede?shelf=read-2014">read-2014</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer468780641" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15541547631985782960"><em>The year is 1957. It‚Äôs just before Christmas in Barcelona and Daniel and Bea are living with their son above the bookstore Sempere &amp; Sons. The faithful servant Ferm√≠n is about to get married. One day an old man visits the bookstore and he wants to buy an old and valuable version of The Count of Monte Cristo. But he doesn‚Äôt take the book with him instead he leaves the books with a dedication‚Ä¶</em><br/><br/>The book continues the story that started in <strong>The Shadow of the Wind</strong> and also has ties with <strong>The Angel&apos;s Gam</strong></span>
  <span id="freeText15541547631985782960" style="display:none"><em>The year is 1957. It‚Äôs just before Christmas in Barcelona and Daniel and Bea are living with their son above the bookstore Sempere &amp; Sons. The faithful servant Ferm√≠n is about to get married. One day an old man visits the bookstore and he wants to buy an old and valuable version of The Count of Monte Cristo. But he doesn‚Äôt take the book with him instead he leaves the books with a dedication‚Ä¶</em><br /><br />The book continues the story that started in <strong>The Shadow of the Wind</strong> and also has ties with <strong>The Angel's Game</strong> which story takes place before <strong>The Shadow of the Wind</strong>. In many ways it‚Äôs a really good story, you get to know what happened to David Martin from <strong>The Angel's Game</strong> and his connection to the Sempere family. Well, you don‚Äôt get all the answers, the ending has a ‚Äúto be continued‚Äù feeling over itself. And since the book had only 300 pages (the Swedish version) and I just think Carlos Ruiz Zaf√≥n could have written well at least 100-200 pages more and just given the book a better ending instead of leaving one hanging. Well, it‚Äôs a smart move because now one just has to have the next book‚Ä¶ when it comes‚Ä¶<br /><br /><strong>The Angel's Game</strong> was such a great book that really pulled you inside and this book for all its promises didn‚Äôt really reach the same level, it was good and I love the connection to <strong>The Count of Monte Cristo</strong> (need to re-read the book), loved to know what happened to David Martin, how and where he wrote his book. I just want more‚Ä¶more Daniel Sempere and more David Martin‚Ä¶more about the Cemetery of Forgotten Books...</span>
