    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_372922275" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/372922275" />
    <a title="TheBookSmugglers" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1223249-thebooksmugglers"><img alt="TheBookSmugglers" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1316717753p2/1223249.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/372922275?book_show_action=true">Jul 20, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="TheBookSmugglers" class="user" itemprop="url" name="TheBookSmugglers" href="/user/show/1223249-thebooksmugglers">TheBookSmugglers</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer372922275" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12542629194248616027">Original review posted on <a href='http://thebooksmugglers.com/2012/07/book-review-the-prisoner-of-heaven-by-carlos-ruiz-zafon.html' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Book Smugglers</a><br/><br/>WARNING! This post contains spoilers!!<br/><br/>Oh, The Prisoner of Heaven, WHY? WHY?<br/><br/>You will have to excuse this sudden display of emotional distress. But I am overcome with feelings and they must be exorcized here.<br/><br/>A few years ago I read The Shadow of the Wind, a tremendous Gothic thriller with labyrinthine storytelling, a wonderful sense of setting, beautiful writing and incredible characters. It soon became a favourite. I do recognise its problems especially </span>
  <span id="freeText12542629194248616027" style="display:none">Original review posted on <a href="http://thebooksmugglers.com/2012/07/book-review-the-prisoner-of-heaven-by-carlos-ruiz-zafon.html" rel="nofollow noopener">The Book Smugglers</a><br /><br />WARNING! This post contains spoilers!!<br /><br />Oh, The Prisoner of Heaven, WHY? WHY?<br /><br />You will have to excuse this sudden display of emotional distress. But I am overcome with feelings and they must be exorcized here.<br /><br />A few years ago I read The Shadow of the Wind, a tremendous Gothic thriller with labyrinthine storytelling, a wonderful sense of setting, beautiful writing and incredible characters. It soon became a favourite. I do recognise its problems especially those concerning the depiction of female characters but since everything else about that book was so good, I was able to enjoy it to a great extent. That said, I always felt that the The Shadow of the Wind was a standalone novel, its main story a self-contained affair ‚Äì even though there was indeed potential for more stories in that world.<br /><br />Cue a few years later and the author published a prequel entitled The Angel‚Äôs Game. Although the same beautiful prose was present, the book turned out to be a great disappointment. A meandering plot, clich√©d characters and a GOTCHA open-for-interpretation clumsy ending and a very loose connection to The Shadow of the Wind made the cynical in me believe The Angel‚Äôs Game to be an afterthought to capitalise on the huge success of that first book.<br /><br />Cue to a few years later and we now have The Prisoner of Heaven. A small introduction tells us that this is part of a cycle of novels in the same literary universe and this labyrinth of stories ‚Äúwhen woven together lead to the heart of the narrative‚Äù.<br /><br />The Prisoner of Heaven is then, as a matter of fact, the third book in what is now, excuse my French, a freaking quartet!<br /><br />In all fairness there is nothing wrong with this idea in principle but in reality, I find its execution to be clumsy and exploitative.<br /><br />The Prisoner of Heaven is narrated once more by The Shadow of the Wind‚Äôs hero Daniel Sempere ‚Äì now married to Bea and with a young child, running the Sempere and Sons bookstore alongside his father. Business is not good and the two Semperes are struggling to make ends meet. Happiness is on the horizon though, as their close friend Ferm√≠n Romero de Torres is about to wed Bernarda, the love of his life. But there is something bothering Ferm√≠n and he is not his usual upbeat self. Just then, a strange figure walks into the bookstore and leaves a message for Ferm√≠n that says:<br /><br />‚ÄúFor Ferm√≠n Romero de Torres, who came back from among the dead and holds the key to the future.‚Äù<br /><br />This prompts Daniel to question Ferm√≠n about his past and those revelations will change everything Daniel knows about not only Ferm√≠n but also about his own family.<br /><br />Ostensibly, The Prisoner of Heaven is Ferm√≠n‚Äôs book. The vast majority of the book is his account of his prison time at the infamous Montju√Øc castle where during the days of Franco‚Äôs dictatorship (in the 40s), political prisoners where held and ‚Äúdisappeared‚Äù. The depiction of the prison and how the prisoners suffered was horrific and affecting.<br /><br />It is there that Ferm√≠n becomes friends with David Martin, no other than the narrator of The Angel‚Äôs Game (!!!!!) (I shall go back to this astounding piece of information later). I have to say though that the description of the horrors suffered by the prisoners inside the prison were completely cheapened by Ferm√≠n‚Äôs daredevil escape ‚Äì in the fashion of Count of Monte Cristo, a scheme devised and organised by David Martin. On that front one must ask: why didn‚Äôt David organise his own escape? Because it didn‚Äôt suit this story, that‚Äôs why.<br /><br />Mind you, there are good things about The Prisoner of Heaven. The writing is still captivating and Ferm√≠n is his usual lovable self. In fact, Ferm√≠n remains a favourite character of mine. His resilience, his heroism, his wits and sense of humour are what make The Prisoner of Heaven at least readable.<br /><br />The Prisoner of Heaven has a series of mysteries that are investigated by Daniel and Ferm√≠n and this construct as well as the very nature of those mysteries were utterly familiar. The ‚Äúwho is this figure who left the message‚Äù, the ‚Äúwhy is this happening‚Äù, the ‚Äúvillain of this story is a piece of shit policeman‚Äù are just SO MUCH like The Shadow of the Wind it‚Äôs not even funny.<br /><br />But the two main problems I had with The Prisoner of Heaven are the way that it rewrites the story of the first two books, and the depiction of the female characters.<br /><br />With regards to the former: all of a sudden, we learn that through his friendship with David Martin, Ferm√≠n has been a part of the Semperes‚Äô life ALL ALONG. That he knew about them, and has been following Daniel since he was a child. All of a sudden, Daniel‚Äôs mother Isabella was murdered as a part of this plot. All of a sudden, David Martin himself is a hero and we are led to question once again his already extremely unreliable narrative in The Angel‚Äôs Game. I get the feeling that this is supposed to enrich the story, to deepen it with the promised ‚Äúnarrative links‚Äù of the introduction. In reality, to me, this has done nothing but to cheapen the stories told so far. I do appreciate that this is a very personal reaction though and I am sure other readers will feel differently.<br /><br />Which brings me to the problematic depiction of the female characters. Although I was able to love the first book despite this obvious problem, I found that this trend has been amplified in The Prisoner of Heaven in a way that it jumps from the pages. The vast majority of the female characters in this series are either prostitutes with a Heart of Gold (always, always described as being past ‚Äútheir prime‚Äù, poor souls to be pitied and lied to about their crumbling beauty) or Impossibly Beautiful Tragic/Angelic figures. Most of the female characters are victims. They are there to be protected, avenged or suspected of foul play.<br /><br />One of the secondary storylines depicts Daniel finding a letter in Bea‚Äôs possession ‚Äì which, by the way, he opens and reads‚Äì and when it turns out to be a love letter from her ex-fianc√©e, Bea becomes the object of Daniel‚Äôs suspicion. This is never fully addressed in the narrative directly with Bea, who never finds out about his suspicions. It is always about Daniel, about what he will do, how he will deal with this. He suspects her because she is too beautiful. To add insult to the injury, toward the end of the novel, there is one random chapter when the narrative is from Bernarda and Bea‚Äôs PoV and it is entirely about the men in their lives.<br /><br />Ultimately, The Prisoner of Heaven reads like a filler novella. It is short, its narrative is full of shortcuts, it is nowhere near as well executed as The Shadow of the Wind and most exasperating of all, it ends on a maddening cliff-hanger in preparation for the final book.<br /><br />I feel no desire to read the last book in this (now) quartet. In fact, I am done with Zafon‚Äôs books for good. It should tell you something that instead of feeling sad, I actually feel relieved for having made this decision. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12542629194248616027" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


