<div id="review_2789683826" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2789683826" />
    <a title="Andrew Smith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5885760-andrew-smith"><img alt="Andrew Smith" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1605605555p2/5885760.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2789683826?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew Smith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew Smith" href="/user/show/5885760-andrew-smith">Andrew Smith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18900805-the-prisoner-of-heaven">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2789683826" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3873983242542396595">In September 2018 Zafon released the fourth, and final, episode of his series featuring the <i>Cemetery of Forgotten Books</i>, a labyrinthine library of obscure and forgotten titles hidden away in the old city of Barcelona. Those lucky enough to be invited into its enclave are permitted to choose just one book from its shelves. In book 1, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1232.The_Shadow_of_the_Wind__The_Cemetery_of_Forgotten_Books___1_' title='The Shadow of the Wind (The Cemetery of Forgotten Books, #1) by Carlos Ruiz Zaf√≥n' rel='nofollow noopener'> The Shadow of the Wind</a> we meet ten-year-old Daniel who has been granted this rare privilege and in due course readers drawn into a world of mystery and intrigue str</span>
  <span id="freeText3873983242542396595" style="display:none">In September 2018 Zafon released the fourth, and final, episode of his series featuring the <i>Cemetery of Forgotten Books</i>, a labyrinthine library of obscure and forgotten titles hidden away in the old city of Barcelona. Those lucky enough to be invited into its enclave are permitted to choose just one book from its shelves. In book 1, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1232.The_Shadow_of_the_Wind__The_Cemetery_of_Forgotten_Books___1_" title="The Shadow of the Wind (The Cemetery of Forgotten Books, #1) by Carlos Ruiz Zaf√≥n" rel="nofollow noopener"> The Shadow of the Wind</a> we meet ten-year-old Daniel who has been granted this rare privilege and in due course readers drawn into a world of mystery and intrigue stretching from 1938 through to the 1970s. The author is on record as having stated that the books can be read in any order, allowing the reader to get to the heart of the narrative via different paths. This may be true but having read, some years ago, the first two books in the series I thought it wise to grab a copy of the rather short book three before launching myself into the massive final tome.<br /><br />In this episode the story is picked up in 1957 and here the central character is really Daniel‚Äôs friend Fermin. Daniel is working in his father‚Äôs book shop one day when a mysterious figure appears and proceeds to purchase a unique, and expensive, illustrated edition of <i>The Count of Monte Cristo</i> before adding a cryptic inscription addressed to Fermin. Leaving delivery of the book to Daniel he exits the shop. As events begin to unfold from this point we learn much more of Fermin‚Äôs history, and in itself this is an interesting tale. Many of the characters here will be familiar to readers who have previously visited this series and whilst the story here is to some extent self contained it really represents another piece in the larger jigsaw puzzle. <br /><br />I did enjoy this book, it‚Äôs strange and atmospheric and the characters are expertly drawn. I finished it too quickly, but at least I have the final book to look forward to. I really can‚Äôt wait to dive back into the world inhabited Daniel, his family, his friends and those that live in the shadows too. As for the idea of reading these books in any order, for me reading them in the order they were published makes sense, but I can see that there is sufficient overlap and self containment to suggest that addressing them in a different sequence might work equally well. If you‚Äôve missed out on these books so far but enjoy mysteries set in times past, then do give this series a try ‚Äì I have a sense you wont regret it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3873983242542396595" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


