<span id="freeTextContainer5815822176337649299">I am sad to say I did not fall head over heels for this book like I did for other books by Zaf√≥n. The first 2/3s of this book dragged on and lacked the atmospheric and mysterious writing that other novels had in the Cemetery of Forgotten Books series. I didn‚Äôt find myself gripped by Ferm√≠n‚Äôs story he was telling Daniel until the very end when David Mart√≠n was brought back to the forefront of the story. <br/><br/>I also wouldn‚Äôt say, like the beginning of this novel stated, that one can read these stories </span>
  <span id="freeText5815822176337649299" style="display:none">I am sad to say I did not fall head over heels for this book like I did for other books by Zaf√≥n. The first 2/3s of this book dragged on and lacked the atmospheric and mysterious writing that other novels had in the Cemetery of Forgotten Books series. I didn‚Äôt find myself gripped by Ferm√≠n‚Äôs story he was telling Daniel until the very end when David Mart√≠n was brought back to the forefront of the story. <br /><br />I also wouldn‚Äôt say, like the beginning of this novel stated, that one can read these stories out of order or on their own. I feel as though a reader would lack a lot of foundational information that‚Äôs provided to you in The Angel‚Äôs Game, if one were to read this first or by itself. So, do what you will with that info. <br /><br />Either way, I hope the fourth book in this series wins me over, because this one was a bust. The writing, at times, was stunning, but it didn‚Äôt feel up to par with the writing and mystery of The Shadow of the Wind. </span>
